\taxon{Definition}
\title{Directed set}
\author{liamoc}
\p{
Formally, a non-empty subset #{Y \subseteq X} of a [poset](dm-0004) #{(X,\sqsubseteq)} is \em{directed} iff: ##{\forall x, y \in Y.\ \exists z \in Y.\ x \sqsubseteq z \land y \sqsubseteq z}
\figure{\tex{\usepackage{tikz}}{
\begin{tikzpicture}
\draw[dotted, thick] (0,0) circle (1.5 cm);
\draw[dotted, thick] (5,0) circle (1.5 cm);	
\node at (2.5,0) {\Huge $\Rightarrow$ };
\node at (2.5,0.6) {$\exists z$ };
\node at (-0.7,-0.5) { \Large $\bullet$ };
\node at (-0.7,-0.8) { $x$ };
\node at (0.7,-0.5) { \Large $\bullet$ };
\node at (0.7,-0.8) { $y$ };
\node (x) at (4.3,-0.5) { \Large $\bullet$ };
\node  at (4.3,-0.8) { $x$ };
\node (y) at (5.7,-0.5) { \Large $\bullet$ };
\node  at (5.7,-0.8) { $y$ };
\node (z)at (5,0.5) { \Large $\bullet$ };
\node  at (5,0.8) { $z$ };
\draw[thick] (x) -- (z)
	  (y) -- (z);
\end{tikzpicture}
}
}
The #{z} above is an [upper bound](dm-000C) of #{x} and #{y}. Hence, a non-empty set is \em{directed} iff every pair of values has an [upper bound](dm-000C) \em{in the set}.}
\p{Intuitively, directed sets are "going somewhere" â€” given two elements we can always find a "greater" one in the set.}

